\section{Mapping}

The mapping is the main part of this work putting the information of the sensors and the sensing into a semantic map containing information about accessible space and obstacles, rooms, room types and objects. The created map is then used for the planning of the search and the navigation of the robot. 

One major design decision for the mapping was the use of a hybrid mapping approach. The used hybrid map combines two paradigms, grid-based and topological. Grid-based maps are accurate metric maps ideal for navigation. However with increasing size they become difficult to keep consistent and less efficient, especially for planning. Topological maps on the other hand are more difficult to use for local navigation, but scale very well. A hybrid map combines the benefits of both map types. Indoor environments are very suitable for such a hybrid map. On a higher level an indoor environment can be described as a topology of rooms and every room can then be described separately in more detail. This is exactly what is done in this work. Every discovered room gets its own grid-based map, not only containing occupancy information but also information about the types of areas in the room and object locations. Each room on the other hand is a node in the high-level topological map capturing the room structure of the environment. When the robot enters another room the grid-based map is changed to the new rooms map. Another benefit of this design is possibility to also split the search problem into two abstraction levels, which will be described later in this thesis.

The second major design decision is to use a $2$D SLAM system based on a Rao-Blackwellized particle filter. One major difficulty is to keep the maps for occupancy, object probabilities and room types and the locations of doorways consistent. The development of a completely new mapping system was out of the scope of this work. Therefore the uncertainty of the SLAM had to be taken into consideration in the mapping of the other information. This is most easily done with SLAM systems using Rao-Blackwellized particle filters, as the uncertainty is represented by particles and their weights and every particle itself has no uncertainty. Therefore all other maps can be created with known pose. The drawback of this approach is that every particle needs its own set of maps, making it only feasible for low particle numbers. However the use of sophisticated sampling techniques in SLAM systems like Gmapping allow for high-quality maps even with low particle numbers. $2D$ SLAM is used as tests with $3D$ SLAM systems showed mediocre results, probably because of the inaccuracy of the RGBD-camera compared to the LIDAR. 

Ultimately the mapping structure is a 2D SLAM system using a Rao-Blackwellized particle filter creating 2D maps using the range measurements of the LIDAR. For every particle a 3D occupancy map (using the depth measurements of the RGBD-camera), a map of object probabilities (using the result of the object detection), a map of room types (using the result of the room type classifier) and a map of doorways (using the result of the door detection) is created. The set of maps of the most probably particle is then used further. On top is a topological mapper keeping track of the discovered rooms, their connections and the current room of the robot. In the following the individual parts of the mapping system are described in more detail. Furthermore the estimation of the object probabilities in the room based on all available information is described at the end of this section.

\subsection{3D mapping and addition of 3D obstacles to the 2D occupancy map}

3D mapping is done using the OctoMap library, which does 3D mapping with known pose using an octree representation. Each node in the octree represents a cube in space and contains a probability value for being occupied. These probabilities are later used in the creation of the object probability map. As some obstacles, like tables, are not sufficiently detectable by the LIDAR the 3D map is also needed for the navigation. The robot can only execute 2D movements, therefore a 2D map containing all obstacles is sufficient. To add the information about obstacles from the 3D map all voxels with an occupancy probability greater than a threshold value are classified as occupied and their projection onto the ground is set occupied in the 2D map for navigation.

\subsection{Object Mapping}

One main idea for object mapping used in this work is to make a three dimensional grid-map containing object probabilities for every object class instead of object tracking. This decision was made as many objects have to be mapped, the confidence of the object detection is not so high and the location in 3D of a detected object is not very accurate. The second idea is to reuse the information about occupancy already mapped in the 3D mapping. Therefore not the actual object probability is mapped but the probability for an object being in a grid cell given it is occupied. This fits well to the result of the object detection. Updating only cells containing a sample will ultimately lead to this conditional probability, as samples are always in occupied cells, if the depth measurements are correct. 

Some assumptions were made to make this problem feasible. The first assumption is the grid cells are independent. This is an assumption regularly made in similar problems, like occupancy grid mapping. The second assumption is independence of different object types. This assumption implies that multiple objects can be located in a grid cell. This is reasonable if the resolution of the grid is rather low. 

Using those assumptions and Bayes' theorem the following formula can be derived: 
\begin{multline}
 P(O_{c}^{o}|I_{1:t}, \mathbf{x}_{1:t},occ_{c}=1) = \\ \frac{P(O_{c}^{o}|I_{t}, \mathbf{x}_{t},occ_{c}=1)P(I_{t}, \mathbf{x}_{t}|occ_{c}=1)P(O_{c}^{o}|I_{1:t-1}, \mathbf{x}_{1:t-1},occ_{C_i}=1)}{P(O_{c}^{o}|occ_{c}=1)P(I_{t}, \mathbf{x}_{t}|I_{1:t-1}, \mathbf{x}_{1:t-1},occ_{c}=1)} = \\ \frac{1}{Z} \frac{P(O_{c}^{o}|I_{t}, \mathbf{x}_{t},occ_{c}=1)P(O_{c}^{o}|I_{1:t-1}, \mathbf{x}_{1:t-1},occ_{C_i}=1)}{P(O_{c}^{o}|occ_{c}=1)}
\end{multline}
$P(O_{c}^{o}|I_{1:t}, \mathbf{x}_{1:t},occ_{c}=1)$ is the probability of cell $c$ containing an object of type $o$ given the RGBD-images $I_{1:t}$, the poses these images were taken at $\mathbf{x}_{1:t}$ and being occupied. $P(O_{c}^{o}|I_{t}, \mathbf{x}_{t},occ_{c}=1)$ is the inverse sensor model, $P(O_{c}^{o}|I_{1:t-1}, \mathbf{x}_{1:t-1},occ_{C_i}=1)$ is the recursive term and $P(O_{c}^{o}|occ_{c}=1)$ is the prior. $Z$ is a normalization term, which can also be calculated by: 
\begin{multline}
 Z=\frac{P(O_{c}^{o}|I_{t}, \mathbf{x}_{t},occ_{c}=1)P(O_{c}^{o}|I_{1:t-1}, \mathbf{x}_{1:t-1},occ_{C_i}=1)}{P(O_{c}^{o}|occ_{c}=1)}+\\ \frac{P(\neg O_{c}^{o}|I_{t}, \mathbf{x}_{t},occ_{c}=1)P(\neg O_{c}^{o}|I_{1:t-1}, \mathbf{x}_{1:t-1},occ_{C_i}=1)}{P(\neg O_{occ,C_i}^{OT}|occ_{c}=1)}
\end{multline}
as the sum of $P(O_{c}^{o}|I_{1:t}, \mathbf{x}_{1:t},occ_{c}=1)$ and $P(\neg O_{c}^{o}|I_{1:t}, \mathbf{x}_{1:t},occ_{c}=1)$ has to be one.

In this problem the prior cannot be set to $0.5$ as multiple uncertain object detection should also result in a relatively high probability. A value of $0.004$ was found to produce in good results.

Finding a suitable inverse sensor model is a difficult task, as it has to cope with the uncertain results of the object detection and there might be other detectable or not detectable objects in the cell.

The chosen inverse sensor model is
\begin{equation}
 P(O_{c}^{o}|I_{t}, \mathbf{x}_{t},occ_{c}=1)=\begin{cases}\max_{s \in \mathbf{S_t^c}} V_hP(O_{s}^{o})+V_m(1-P(O_{s}^{o})) & |\mathbf{S_t^{c}}| > 0 \\P(O_{c}^{o}|occ_{c}=1) & |\mathbf{S_t^c}| = 0 \end{cases}                                            
\end{equation}
with $P(O_{s}^{o})$ being the probability for object type $o$ of sample $s$. $\mathbf{S_t^{C_i}}$ is the set of samples of the result of the object detection on image $I_t$ falling into cell $C_i$. $V_h$ and $V_m$ are parameters modeling the uncertainty of this approach.

In words, the inverse sensor is the highest probability for an object type of all samples falling into a cell with additional application of uncertainty. The assumptions behind this approach is that the sample with the highest probability is on the object, the other samples are on other obstacles in the cell.

The problem of pixels in a bounding box not belonging to the object is not explicitly handled in this approach. Suitable values for the parameters $V_h$ and $V_m$ and the use of many images should however cope with this problem.

The final probability of an object of type $o$ being in a cell is
\begin{equation}
 P(O_{c}^{o}|I_{t}, \mathbf{x}_{t})=P(O_{c}^{o}|I_{t}, \mathbf{x}_{t},occ_{c}=1)P(occ_{c}=1|I_{t}, \mathbf{x}_{t})                                            
\end{equation}
as the probability of a cell containing an object is zero if the cell is not occupied. 

\subsection{Room Type Mapping}

Assigning a single room type to a whole room is not sufficient for many rooms. One the one hand it is quiet common that different types of rooms, like a kitchen and a living room, are only partially or not at all separated by walls. On the other hand more accurate classes can often be found for areas in a room, like a pantry-like area in a kitchen. Therefore a room type map is created for every room. This room type map is a 2D grid map, where each grid cell has its own probability distribution over the detectable room types. 

The mapping procedure is similar to the object mapping and also assumes independent grid cells. Therefore the update formula, similar to the object mapping formula, is:
\begin{multline}
 P(R_{c}|I_{1:t}, \mathbf{x}_{1:t}) = \\ \frac{P(R_{c}|I_{t}, \mathbf{x}_{t})P(I_{t}, \mathbf{x}_{t})P(R_{c}|I_{1:t-1}, \mathbf{x}_{1:t-1})}{P(R_{c})P(I_{t}, \mathbf{x}_{t}|I_{1:t-1}, \mathbf{x}_{1:t-1})} = \\ \frac{1}{Z} \frac{P(R_{c}|I_{t}, \mathbf{x}_{t})P(R_{c}|I_{1:t-1}, \mathbf{x}_{1:t-1})}{P(R_{c})}
\end{multline}

$P(R_{c}|I_{1:t}, \mathbf{x}_{1:t})$ is the probability distribution over the detectable room types of cell $c$ given the RGBD-images $I_{1:t}$ and the poses these images were taken at $\mathbf{x}_{1:t}$. $P(R_{c}|I_{t}, \mathbf{x}_{t})$ is the inverse sensor model, $P(R_{c}|I_{1:t-1}, \mathbf{x}_{1:t-1})$ is the recursive term and $P(R_{c})$ is the prior. Presuming no prior knowledge the prior $P(R_{c})$ is set to $\frac{1}{|\mathbf{R}|}$, with $|\mathbf{R}|$ being the number of detectable room types. $Z$ is a normalization term, which can also be calculated by: 
\begin{equation}
 Z=\sum_{R_c} \frac{P(R_{c}|I_{t}, \mathbf{x}_{t})P(R_{c}|I_{1:t-1}, \mathbf{x}_{1:t-1})}{P(R_{c})}
\end{equation}
as the probabilities have to sum to $1$. 

The inverse sensor model $P(R_{c}|I_{t}, \mathbf{x}_{t})$ uses the result of the room type classification for the image $I_t$, $P(R_{I_{t} }|I_t)$. It has also to take into account which cells are visible. A simple approach is used, assuming all cells with a cell center within the view cone of the camera, which are also within a certain range, are visible. This is illustrated in Figure \ref{fig:room_type_update}. A more complex estimation of the seen area is not used as it is difficult to estimate which cells are visible enough to contribute to the room type classification and how much each visible cell contributes to the classification. However the used simplistic estimation of the visible cells leads to invisible cells being updated. As these wrongly updated invisible cells are most of the time behind a wall and space outside the room is ignored in later stages of the system, the impact of wrongly updated cells should be small.

\begin{figure}[h]
\centering
  \includegraphics[width=0.5\textwidth, trim = 100 100 70 80, clip]{figures/room_type_update.pdf}
  \caption{The cells updated in the room type map using the image taken at the robot position marked with the arrow, light gray cells are later ignored for being behind a wall and outside the room}
  \label{fig:room_type_update}
\end{figure}

Also to be considered is that not all cells visible in an image have to be of the same room type. The connection between classification result and room type probability of the cell base on the classified image is given by the following formula: 
\begin{equation}
P(R_{c}|I_{t},\mathbf{x}_{t}) = \begin{cases}\sum_{R_{I_{t} }} P(R_{I_{t} }|I_t) \; P(R_{c}|R_{I_{t}})  & if \;cell \; c \; visible\\P(R_{c}) & else\end{cases}
\end{equation}

$P(R_{c}|R_{I_{t}})$ is the probability of the room type of a cell $c$ given the room type mainly shown in the image. The combinations form a $|\mathbf{R}|$x$|\mathbf{R}|$ matrix. The diagonal elements, where $R_{c} = R_{I_{t}}$, are to a parameter $V_{eq}$. Instead of presuming no prior knowledge and making all other values equal, prior knowledge is gathered to get better mapping results. The off-diagonal elements are weighted based on how related the two room types are. How much two room types are related is estimated using Divisi2, a library for extraction of information from commonsense databases.

\subsection{Doorway Mapping}

The doorway mapping is responsible for adding doorway locations and orientations into the map. Therefore the doorways found by the doorway detection are transformed into the map frames of the particles. For every detected doorway has to be decided, if it is a new doorway or another detection of a already found doorway. If the distance between a detection and an already found doorway is greater than a threshold distance, as new doorway is inserted into the map. Otherwise the doorway fitting best to the detection, based on distance and orientation, is updated. This is show in figure \ref{fig:door_mapping}. A running average filter is used to estimate the true doorway pose. As the direction of a doorway is always away from the robot, door poses are always pointing out of the room. The doorway mapper is initialized already containing a doorway, which is the doorway the room was entered. How this is done is described later in this work. There is one exception to this, which is the door mapper of the initial room, as this room was never entered.

\begin{figure}[h]
\centering
  \includegraphics[width=0.5\textwidth, clip]{figures/door_mapping.png}
  \caption{Door mapping example: The red arrow is the current robot pose, the green arrows are already found doorways and the yellow arrow is the result of the door detection, which is used to update the pose of the nearby doorway}
  \label{fig:door_mapping}
\end{figure}

\subsection{Object Probability Map Estimation}

This subsection describes how the information in the different types of maps of a room are put together to obtain a estimation of the object probability at all locations in the room. This includes the estimation of the room type in location only seen by the LIDAR, the estimation of the object probabilities based on the room type map and the combination of those estimates with the object maps.

\subsubsection{Room types in locations only seen by the LIDAR}

The LIDAR has a field of view of 120°, while the RGBD-camera has only a horizontal field of view of 58°. This can lead to areas, which were only seen by the LIDAR, which can be seen in Figure \ref{fig:seen}. 
\begin{figure}[h]
\centering
  \includegraphics[width=0.8\textwidth, clip]{figures/seen.png}
  \caption{An explored room, light areas were only seen by the LIDAR}
  \label{fig:seen}
\end{figure}
Only the occupied ones of these cells are of interest, as free cells are assumed to contain no objects. The estimation is done in two steps. In a first step the room type of these cells is estimated. Therefore the probability distribution over the room type of cells never seen with the RGBD-camera are set to the average probability distribution in the room. To also consider the neighborhood of the cell a Gaussian filter with the kernel $G(\Delta x, \Delta y)$ is applied:
\begin{equation}
 P(R_{c,filtered}|I_{1:t}, \mathbf{x}_{1:t})= \sum_{c_2 \in Cells}G(\Delta x, \Delta y)P(R_{c_2}|I_{1:t}, \mathbf{x}_{1:t})
\end{equation}
Using the correlation between room type of an area and objects in the area the object probability can be estimated.

\subsubsection{Object probabilities based on the room type map}

As already described there exists a correlation between the room type of an area and the objects located in this area. This correlation is captured in the matrix M, which contains the probability of an object $o$ being in an image of an area of a room type $r$. In a first step this probability has to be adapted to be the probability of an object of type $o$ being in a grid cell of room type of type $r$. To do this correctly information about the number of cells usually seen in an image and the number of cells being occupied by an object would be needed. As these are difficult to estimate the probabilities are simply multiplied by a parameter $V_corr$ empirically found, resulting in the per cell correlation matrix being:
\begin{equation}
 C_{r,o}=V_{corr} M_{r,o}
\end{equation}

The probability of an object being in a cell based on the probability distribution of the room type of the cell $P(O_{R,c}^{o}|I_{1:t}, \mathbf{x}_{1:t})$ can be calculated with: 
\begin{equation}
 P(O_{R,c}^{o}|I_{1:t}, \mathbf{x}_{1:t})= \sum_{R_{c}}P(R_{c}|I_{1:t}, \mathbf{x}_{1:t})P(O_{R,c}^{o}|R_c)=\sum_{R_{c}}P(R_{c}|I_{1:t}, \mathbf{x}_{1:t})C_{R_{c},o}
\end{equation}

\subsubsection{Object probabilities based on all information}

The information in the object map has to be combined with the information from the room type map. This is done with the following formula:
\begin{equation}
 P(Obj_{c}^{o}|I_{1:t}, \mathbf{x}_{1:t})=\frac{1}{Z}P(O_{R,c}^{o}|I_{1:t}, \mathbf{x}_{1:t})P(O_{c}^{o}|I_{1:t}, \mathbf{x}_{1:t})
\end{equation}

$Z$ is a normalization term, as the $P(Obj_{c}^{o}|I_{1:t}, \mathbf{x}_{1:t}) + P(\neg Obj_{c}^{o}|I_{1:t}, \mathbf{x}_{1:t}) = 1$ and can be calculated with:
\begin{equation}
 Z=P(O_{R,c}^{o}|I_{1:t}, \mathbf{x}_{1:t})P(O_{c}^{o}|I_{1:t}, \mathbf{x}_{1:t})+P(\neg O_{R,c}^{o}|I_{1:t}, \mathbf{x}_{1:t})P(\neg O_{c}^{o}|I_{1:t}, \mathbf{x}_{1:t})
\end{equation}


\subsection{Topological Mapping and Room Transitioning}

The topological map consists of nodes for every room, which contains the room maps and condensed information for the high-level planning based on the room maps. It also contains edges, where each edge corresponds to a doorway and holds information about which rooms are connected and the pose of the connecting doorway in both rooms. The topological mapping is responsible for the creation of this graphical structure, including the initialization of new room maps, the localization in the topological map and the handling room transitions. 

When a new doorway is found a new node is inserted into the graph with an edge connecting the node of the current room and the new node. An empty semantic room map is assigned to the new node. In this map the newly detected doorway is then inserted to have a valid connection between the two rooms with the doorway pose in both rooms. The pose has the same position as in the other room, but is 180° degree rotated, so it faces out of the room. In this work environments are assumed to have no loops, meaning there is only one way into a room given a starting room. Therefore the room behind a newly found doorway cannot be already discovered. 

When a doorway is passed the room map has to be switched. A doorway is passed if the robot is more than a threshold distance in front of the doorway. This is marked by the blue line on the left Figure \ref{fig:doors}. The threshold is important to achieve a hysteresis and avoid switching back and forth. In a first step the mapping in the left room is stopped. Then the particles in the new rooms particle filter have to be set to meaningful poses. Therefore the poses of the particles in the old rooms particle filter are transformed into the new rooms coordinate frame with:
\begin{equation}
 \mathbf{P_{new}}=P_{D_{new}}T_{flip}P_{D_{old}}^{-1}\mathbf{P_{old}}
\end{equation}

$P_{old}$ and $P_{new}$ are the particle pose in the old and new room coordinate frames, $P_{D_{old}}$ and $P_{D_{new}}$ are the pose of the doorway in the old and new room and $T_{flip}$ is a 180° rotation, which is necessary as in both rooms the doorway pose faces outward. In a third step all particles except the best one in the old rooms particle filter are discarded, as those particles are not meaningful when the robot returns to the room. In the last step the mapping in the new room is started. Figure \ref{fig:doors} shows the map before and after a doorway passing. The maps contain also space in the other room. This is necessary for navigation through the doorway. For the search planning space behind a doorway is ignored.

\begin{figure}[h]
\centering
  \subfloat[Room before doorway passing]{{\includegraphics[width=0.45\textwidth, trim = 0 20 0 25, clip]{figures/door_gang.png} }}%
  \qquad
  \subfloat[Room after doorway passing]{{\includegraphics[width=0.45\textwidth]{figures/door_wz.png} }}%
  \caption{2 Figures side by side}%
  \label{fig:doors}
\end{figure}

\subsection{High-Level Room Information Generation}

For the high level planner to work the information in the room maps has to be condensed into easier to used room attributes. These are
\begin{itemize}
 \item the probability of an object of the searched object type being in the room
 \item the time needed to completely search the room
 \item the expected time the robot searches in the room until an object of searched type is found or the room is completely searched 
 \item the time to traverse the room for all doorway pairs
\end{itemize}

The time needed for exploration is ignored, as it is hard to estimate and this way an incentive for exploration over searching in unlikely rooms is added.

\subsubsection{Object probability in room r $\mathbf{P_r(O)}$}

No object of the searched object type is in the room if no cell in the room contains an object of that type. The probability of a searched object being in the room is simply 1 minus this probability. The cells taken into account are all cells, where at least one sample of the object detection was in and are denoted by $\mathbf{C_{exp}}$. For not fully explored rooms also the number of not explored cells possibly containing the object $N_{unexp}$ and their object probability $P(Obj_{unexp}^o)$ have to be estimated. The object probability is therefore calculated with:
\begin{multline}
 P(Obj^o|I_{1:t}, \mathbf{x}_{1:t})=\\1-\Big(\prod_{c \in \mathbf{C_{exp}}} (1-P(Obj_{c}^{o}|I_{1:t}, \mathbf{x}_{1:t}))\Big) (1-P(Obj_{unexp}^o))^{N_{unexp}} 
\end{multline}

The estimation of the number of unexplored, occupied cells is done in a simplistic way, as meaningful complex models are hard to design with the limited amount of available test data. It is calculated with:
\begin{equation}
 N_{unexp}=max(N_{default}-|\mathbf{C_{exp}}|, N_{min})
\end{equation}
$N_{default}$ is a basic estimate of the size of an unexplored room and $N_{min}$ is the minimal number of unexplored cells, if the room is not fully explored. The 

fixed parameter, which is the estimated number of occupied cells in a completely unexplored room, minus the number of explored occupied cells, greater or equal a second parameter. This second parameter is needed as the number of explored occupied cells can be greater than the first parameter and the room can still be not fully explored. If the room is fully explored, the number number of unexplored, occupied cells is obviously zero. A more sophisticated model was not chosen as a more realistic, better performing model is hard to find and would also need a lot of data to find reasonable parameters.

The estimation of the probability density is done based on the average room type probability in the room and the room-type-object-correlation matrix. Therefore, with the expected number of unexplored, occupied cells $N_{unexp}$ and the average room type probability $P(R_{avg})$ 
\begin{equation}
 P(O_{R,unexp}^{OT})=1-(1-\sum_{r \in \mathbf{RT}}P(R_{avg})*P(O_{R,unexp}^{OT}|R_{avg}))^{N_{unexp}} 
\end{equation}

\subsubsection{Complete Search Time in room r $\mathbf{T_r}$}

The time needed to search a room is difficult to estimate, as it depends on what the search planner is doing and especially on how well the navigation works. Based on the map is hardly possible to estimate, how fast the robot can drive between view poses and how often a recovery behavior has to be executed. As the generation of a lot of test data is impossible a minimalistic model is used. 

The number of occupied cells in the 2D map has a high correlation with the search time. A high number means many possible object locations and also many obstacles, which can cause problems for the navigation. Therefore the time needed to completely search a room is the number of occupied cells in the 2D map in a room times a parameter found in test runs.

\subsubsection{Estimated Search Time in room r $\mathbf{E_r}$}

The estimated search time is the expected value for the time the robot is searching in a room calculated with
\begin{equation}
 E_r(O) = \int_{0}^\infty f_r^O(t)\cdot t\cdot dt
\end{equation}

The search ends if the object is found or the room is completely searched. Therefore the probability distribution of ending the search over time $f_r(t)$ is
\begin{equation}
 f_r^O(t)=(1-P_r(O))\delta(T_r)+f_{find,r}^O(t)
\end{equation}
with $f_{find,r}^O(t)$ being the probability distribution over time for finding the object, which has to fulfill 
\begin{equation}
 \int_{0}^\infty f_{find,r}^O(t)\cdot dt = P_r(O)
\end{equation}
and
\begin{equation}
 f_{find,r}^O(t) = 0 \;\; \forall \; t < 0, t > T_r
\end{equation}

The estimation of $f_{find,r}^O(t)$ is done by discretization of time. To calculate the probability of finding the object in a time step $[T_{i-1},T_i)$ the object probabilities of all cells in the room are sorted and assigned to the time steps in decreasing order. The probability of finding the object in a certain time step $[T_{i-1},T_i)$, $P_i$, is then calculated with
\begin{equation}
 P_{i}=\prod_{j=1}^{i-1}(1-P_{j}) \cdot (1-\prod_{c \in \mathbf{C_i}}(1-P(O_{R,c}^{OT}|I_{1:t},\mathbf{x}_{1:t}))
\end{equation}
This model was chosen as it takes into account the distribution of object probabilities in the room and the decreasing probability of finding an object due to the objective of the search planner. The estimated search time is then
\begin{equation}
 E_r(O)=\sum_i P_iT_i+(1-P_r(O))T_r 
\end{equation}

\subsubsection{Movement time between room r1 and r2 $\mathbf{M_{r1,r2}}$}

Movement time between rooms has to be further specified, as rooms are areas and not positions and the movement within a room is not neglectable. In this context the movement time is measured from the the doorway, where the room is left, to the doorway leading into the target room and an estimated time for the movement within the first room is added.

For the estimation of the movement time between two points a simple model is used, which calculates the time by multiplying the distance between the points with a empirically determined parameter. A more complex model using the length of a planned path is not used as the calculation is much more time-consuming. Further such a model does not take into account how fast the robot will drive on this path and how likely a recovery behavior will be executed.

To calculate the movement times a graph is created with every doorway being a node and an edge between two nodes if the doorways are in one room. The weight of the edge is the movement time between the doorways estimated as described above. The Floyd-Warshall algorithm is applied on the graph resulting in a matrix containing the shortest paths between two doorways and also the nodes to traverse can be retrieved. 

The time to leave the starting room through a certain doorway depends on the location of the robot. This location is not known in when planning ahead as it depends on where the robot ends a room search, which is not known in advance. So the location is assumed to be the center of mass of all accessible cells in the grid map. The time to leave the room through a doorway is then estimated based on the distance to the doorway as explained above. 

The full movement time between to rooms is then the sum of the time calculated using the doorway graph and the time to move to the first doorway. As no loops are assumed there is no loss of optimality by not considering the leave-time in the shortest path calculation.

% The goal of the object mapping to store the information where objects were seen. There are lots of objects in indoor environments and the object detections accuracy is far from perfect. Therefore the representation as a list of found objects with location and category and the tracking of those objects is infeasible. A representation by a three dimensional grid map with a probability for every object class for every cell looked far more promising. For this approach to work the probabilities of different object types were assumed to be independent. This assumption was made to simplify the problem and was made because it is possible that multiple different objects are located within one cell. The second assumption is that the probabilities of different cells are independent. With these assumptions the update can be done similar to the update in occupancy grid mapping for every object class.
% 
